{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{italic title}} {{Infobox artwork |image=Peter Paul Rubens (1577-1640), Portrait of a commander, Christie's Images.jpg |title=Portrait of a Commander |artist=[[Peter Paul Rubens]] (?) |year=c.1613 (?) |height_metric=122.6 |width_metric=98.2 |museum=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |city=[[New York City|New York]] |website= |medium=oil on panel |accession= }}
'''''Portrait of a Commander''''' or '''''A Commander Being Dressed for Battle''''' is a portrait of an unknown man in [[plate armour]], normally attributed to [[Peter Paul Rubens]]. In July 2010 it was sold for £9 million by [[Christie's]]<ref name=christies>{{cite web |url=http://www.christies.com/lotfinder/paintings/sir-peter-paul-rubens-portrait-of-a-5339055-details.aspx |title=Sir Peter Paul Rubens (Siegen, Westphalia 1577–1640 Antwerp)|publisher=[[Christie's]]|year=2013|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref> after [[Sotheby's]] turned it down, suspecting its authenticity as a Rubens.<ref name=bell>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/art-historians-cast-doubt-over-earl-spencers-1639m-rubens-2023989.html |title=Art historians cast doubt over Earl Spencer's £9m Rubens|first=Matthew|last=Bell|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=31 December 2013|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In December 2011, the portrait was placed on loan with the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artsjournal.com/culturegrrl/2012/03/met_gets_a_137-million_rubens.html |title=Met Displays Controversial $13.7-Million "Commander," Sold by Princess Diana's Brother|first=Lee|last=Rosenbaum|date=7 March 2012|accessdate=31 December 2013|publisher=Arts Journal}}</ref>
==Description== The painting, done in [[Oil painting|oil]] on panel,<ref name=christies/> measures 48.25 × 38 3/8 in. (122.6 × 98.2 cm).<ref name=christies/> It depicts a military commander, as shown by his [[Baton (symbol)|baton]], being dressed by [[Page (servant)|page]]s. The identity of the commander is unknown, although [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]],<ref name=reuters>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/03/29/us-finearts-princessdiana-idUSTRE62S31H20100329 |title=Princess Diana family offers Rubens in $30 million sale |first=Mike |last=Collett-White|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=29 March 2010|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref> [[Cornelis van der Geest]],<ref name=doubt>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1293877/Is-Earl-Spencer-Rubens-9m-fake-Experts-cast-doubt-provenance-painting.html |title=Is the Earl Spencer Rubens a £9m fake? Experts cast doubt over provenance of painting |first=Lucy|last=Ballinger|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=31 December 2013|work=[[Daily Mail]]}}</ref> and the [[Fernando Álvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba|Duke of Alba]]<ref name=christies/> have all been identified as possible subjects. The Christie's cataloguer felt that the commander appears too idealized to be an actual person.<ref name=christies/> The painting has been praised for its crisp and intense hue and the reflective properties of the armour.<ref name=artinfo>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.artinfo.com/artintheair/2010/07/13/rubens-buyer-stays-cool-amid-attribution-questions/ |title=Rubens Buyer Stays Cool Amid Attribution Questions|date=13 July 2010|accessdate=31 December 2013|publisher=Artinfo}}</ref> If by Rubens, it would have been painted around 1613.<ref name=doubt/>
==History== The [[provenance]] of the work before 1802 is uncertain, with Christie's adding "(possibly)" to almost every paragraph in their description,<ref name=bell/> until it came into the possession of [[George Spencer, 2nd Earl Spencer]] by 1802.<ref name=christies/> After that it remained the property of the Spencer family until 2010, when [[Charles Spencer, 9th Earl Spencer]], brother of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], decided to auction it with nearly 800 other artworks not deemed core to the [[Althorp]] collection<ref name=reuters/> in order to raise funds for restoration work at the estate.<ref name=bell/> It was sold at the lower end of the Christie's estimate of between £8m and £12m to Konrad Bernheimer for £9 million ($13.7 million).<ref name=artinfo/> This is the second highest price ever paid for Rubens' work at auction,<ref name=bell/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/pound21m-auction-boost-for-spencer-estate-2022408.html |title=£21m auction boost for Spencer estate |first=Elizabeth|last=Barrett|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=31 December 2013|work=The Independent}}</ref> after the ''[[Massacre of the Innocents (Rubens)|Massacre of the Innocents]]'', now in [[Toronto]], which was sold at Sotheby's in London on 10 July 2002, for £49.5 million to Canadian businessman and art collector [[Kenneth Thomson, 2nd Baron Thomson of Fleet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/2119451.stm |work=BBC News|date=11 July 2002|title=Rubens fetches record £49.5m|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suebond.co.uk/events/release.php?eventid=289 |title=Rubens's The Massacre of the Innocents at The Thomson Collection|publisher=Sue Bond}} (press release)</ref>
==Authenticity== For more than 100 years, it was attributed to the "School of [[Frans Pourbus the Younger|Porbus]]".<ref name=bell/> It was not attributed to Rubens until after World War II.<ref name=christies /><ref name=bell/> According to [[Brian Sewell]], it is an "uncomfortable Rubens" and the attribution "doesn't quite ring true".<ref name=bell/> A panel of academics employed by Christie's examined the portrait and ultimately concluded that the painting is a genuine Rubens.<ref name=christies/> <gallery> File:The Gallery of Cornelis van der Geest.JPG|''The Gallery of [[Cornelis van der Geest]]'', by [[Willem van Haecht]] shows this painting hanging on the rear wall. </gallery>
==References== {{Reflist|2}}
