{{UK-art-historian-stub}}

{{refimprove|date=September 2016}}
'''Solid perfumes''' or cream perfumes are [[perfume]]s in solid state rather than the liquid mix of alcohol ([[ethanol]]) and water used in [[eau de parfum]], [[eau de toilette]], [[eau de cologne]], etc.  Normally the substance that gives the cream its base comes from a type of [[wax]] that is initially melted. Once melted, a [[scent]] or several scents may be added.  

Solid perfume is used either by rubbing a finger or dipping a [[cotton swab]] against it and then onto the skin. Sometimes solid perfume can take more time for the [[deeper note]]s to come out than a [[spray (liquid drop)|spray]] perfume.

The latest solid perfumes are designed as handbag aromas, so a compact way of making perfume more portable.

Historically, [[ointment]]-like [[unguents]] have been used as a type of solid perfume since [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] times.<ref>[http://egyptmonth.com/mag08012000/mag4.htm Perfumes of Ancient Egypt] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012170326/http://egyptmonth.com/mag08012000/mag4.htm |date=2007-10-12 }}</ref>
